<HEADLINE>
<P>
OFF-THE-WALL STREET 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Is Wall Street dull? No. Are the people who work in Wall Street dull? Probably, 
but no more so than any pedestrian. 
</P>
<P>
I have worked with any number of "street" people for the last 22 years and got 
to know them fairly well. Analysts, retail brokers, corporate finance syndicate 
men, investment bankers, market makers, money managers. Have I left anyone out? 
Of all that number there is only one I could say is in any way colorful: Noble 
Trenham, who owns First Global Securities. You think I am making that up, don't 
you? 
</P>
<P>
Wall Street, on the inside, is intricate, finely tuned, and sensitively 
balanced, like a clock. But, as with a clock, we are not interested in what 
goes on inside. We just want to look at the face and see what time it is. Wall 
Street is like that. 
</P>
<P>
PAUL GROPMAN 
</P>
<P>
SHERMAN OAKS 
</P>
</TEXT>
